x4freetext: ORELA
200-m flight path. The 140-MeV pulsed electron
beam provided 4-nsec neutron burstswith a continuous
energy spectrum produced by the photoneutron process
in the tantalum target and subsequent moderation in
the 15-cm-diameter, beryllium clad, water-filled
target housing.
Neutrons were detected from the proton recoils
as they traversed a 2.54-cm thickness of a 5.2 cm x
8.9 cm piece of NE110 scintillator
A sample of 54Cr2O3. The oxide sample had a weight of
19.9615 g with percentage abundances of 95.40, 3.09,
0.18, and 1.33 of 54Cr, 52Cr, 50Cr, and 53Cr,
respectively. The inverse Cr thickness of the 54Cr2O3
sample was 18.48 b/atom.
Measurements employed the time-of-flight
technique, using neutron pulses from the ORELA.
The averaged transmission data were analyzed using the
Reich-Moore formulation of the R-matrix theory
